text: Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) Introduction to Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) A Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) is a specialized class of deep neural networks primarily designed to process grid-like data, such as images (2D grids of pixels), videos (3D: height × width × time), and even audio spectrograms. CNNs are the backbone of most modern computer vision systems. They automatically learn spatial features (edges, textures, shapes, objects) from raw input data with minimal manual feature engineering. Why CNNs are Needed Traditional fully connected neural networks (ANNs) face major issues when dealing with images: 1. High dimensionality o A 224×224 RGB image has 150,528 input features o Fully connected layers lead to millions of parameters 2. Loss of spatial information o ANNs flatten images → spatial relationships are lost 3. Overfitting & computation cost CNNs solve these problems by: • Local connectivity • Weight sharing • Hierarchical feature learning Biological Inspiration CNNs are inspired by the visual cortex of the human brain: • Neurons respond to local regions of the visual field • Simple cells detect edges • Complex cells detect shapes and objects Core Idea of CNN CNNs use convolution operations to: • Detect local patterns • Preserve spatial structure • Learn features automatically Instead of learning all pixel relationships, CNNs focus on local receptive fields. Basic Architecture of CNN A typical CNN consists of the following layers: Input → Convolution → Activation → Pooling → (Repeat) → Fully Connected → Output 2. Convolution Layer (Core of CNN) What is Convolution? A mathematical operation where a filter (kernel) slides over the image to produce a feature map. Kernel / Filter • Small matrix (e.g., 3×3, 5×5) • Learns to detect features such as: o Edges o Corners o Textures Operation Each output pixel is: Output = Sum(Input × Kernel) + Bias Parameters • Stride (S): step size of filter movement • Padding (P): adding zeros around input to preserve size o Valid padding → no padding o Same padding → output size = input size Output Size Formula Output = (N − F + 2P) / S + 1 Where: • N = input size • F = filter size 4. Pooling Layer (Downsampling) Purpose • Reduce spatial dimensions • Reduce computation • Provide translation invariance Types 1. Max Pooling (most common) 2. Average Pooling 3. Global Average Pooling Example: 2×2 Max Pooling → picks maximum value Training a CNN Loss

text: N = input size • F = filter size 4. Pooling Layer (Downsampling) Purpose • Reduce spatial dimensions • Reduce computation • Provide translation invariance Types 1. Max Pooling (most common) 2. Average Pooling 3. Global Average Pooling Example: 2×2 Max Pooling → picks maximum value Training a CNN Loss Functions • Categorical Cross-Entropy • Binary Cross-Entropy • MSE (for regression) Optimization Algorithms • SGD • Adam • RMSProp Backpropagation • Gradients are computed • Filters are updated automatically Key Advantages of CNN 1. Automatic feature extraction 2. Fewer parameters (weight sharing) 3. Spatial invariance 4. High accuracy for vision tasks Limitations of CNN 1. Requires large datasets 2. Computationally expensive 3. Poor rotation & scale invariance (without augmentation) 4. Hard to interpret Applications of CNN • Image classification (ImageNet) • Face recognition • Object detection (YOLO, Faster R-CNN) • Medical imaging • Autonomous vehicles • OCR & handwriting recognition • Video analysis Popular CNN Architectures • LeNet-5 • AlexNet • VGGNet • GoogLeNet (Inception) • ResNet • MobileNet • EfficientNet

text: Syllabus: Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) 1. Introduction to CNN • Definition of Convolutional Neural Networks • Motivation for CNNs in image and spatial data processing • Comparison of CNNs with traditional Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) • Biological inspiration from the human visual cortex • Applications of CNNs in computer vision 2. Image Representation and Input Layer • Digital image representation (Grayscale and RGB images) • Image dimensions and channels • Input layer structure in CNN • Preprocessing of image data 3. Convolution Operation • Concept of convolution • Filters (kernels) and feature maps • Local receptive fields • Weight sharing mechanism • Mathematical formulation of convolution • Hyperparameters: o Kernel size o Stride o Padding (valid and same) • Output size calculation 4. Activation Functions in CNN • Role of non-linearity in CNNs • ReLU activation function • Problems addressed by ReLU (vanishing gradient) • Variants of ReLU: o Leaky ReLU o PReLU o ELU 5. Pooling Layers • Purpose of pooling • Downsampling and dimensionality reduction • Types of pooling: o Max Pooling o Average Pooling o Global Average Pooling • Effect of pooling on translation invariance 6. Feature Learning and Hierarchical Representation • Shallow vs deep CNNs • Hierarchical feature extraction • Low-level, mid-level, and high-level features • Stacking multiple convolution layers 7. Fully Connected Layers • Flattening operation • Role of dense layers in CNN • Transition from feature extraction to classification 8. Output Layer and Prediction • Output layer design • Activation functions: o Softmax for multi-class classification o Sigmoid for binary classification • Regression output using linear activation 9. Training of CNN • Loss functions: o Categorical Cross-Entropy o Binary Cross-Entropy o Mean Squared Error (MSE) • Backpropagation in CNN • Optimization algorithms: o Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) o Adam o RMSProp • Weight and bias updates 10. Advantages and Limitations of CNN • Advantages: o Automatic feature extraction o Parameter efficiency o Spatial invariance • Limitations: o Large data requirement o High computational cost o Limited rotation and scale invariance o Interpretability issues 11. Applications of CNN • Image classification • Face recognition • Object detection and localization • Medical image analysis • Autonomous driving • Optical Character Recognition (OCR) • Video analysis 12. Popular CNN Architectures • LeNet-5 • AlexNet • VGGNet • GoogLeNet (Inception) • ResNet • MobileNet • EfficientNet 13. Summary and Future Scope • Role of CNNs in modern deep

Popular CNN Architectures • LeNet-5 • AlexNet • VGGNet • GoogLeNet (Inception) • ResNet • MobileNet • EfficientNet 13. Summary and Future Scope • Role of CNNs in modern deep learning • Integration of CNNs with other models • Trends in CNN research and applications

text: Fundamentals of Artificial Intelligence (AI) Introduction to Artificial Intelligence Artificial Intelligence (AI) is a branch of computer science that focuses on creating intelligent machines capable of performing tasks that require human intelligence such as learning, reasoning, problem-solving, perception, and decision-making. Definitions of AI John McCarthy defined AI as the science and engineering of making intelligent machines. Russell and Norvig define AI as the study of intelligent agents. Goals of AI Learning from data, reasoning, problem solving, knowledge representation, natural language understanding, perception, and autonomous decision-making. Types of Artificial Intelligence Narrow AI (task-specific), General AI (human-level intelligence), and Super AI (beyond human intelligence). Core Components of AI Data, algorithms, and models form the foundation of AI systems. Fundamental Areas of AI Machine Learning, Knowledge Representation, Reasoning and Inference, Search and Problem Solving, Natural Language Processing, Computer Vision, and Robotics. Machine Learning Machine learning enables systems to learn from data without explicit programming. Types include supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement learning. AI Agents An AI agent perceives its environment through sensors and acts upon it using actuators. Types include simple reflex, model-based, goal-based, utility-based, and learning agents. AI vs ML vs Deep Learning AI is the broad field, ML is a subset of AI, and Deep Learning is a subset of ML based on neural networks. Applications of AI Healthcare, finance, education, transportation, manufacturing, and customer support. Advantages of AI High accuracy, automation, faster decision-making, and continuous availability. Limitations of AI High cost, data dependency, lack of creativity, ethical and privacy issues. Ethical and Responsible AI Fairness, transparency, explainability, privacy, and accountability are critical considerations. Future Scope of AI Explainable AI, Edge AI, human-AI collaboration, and responsible AI development.
subject: Fundamentals_of_AI

text: 50 MCQs: Fundamentals of Artificial Intelligence (AI) 1. Artificial Intelligence is a branch of: a) Electrical Engineering b) Computer Science c) Mechanical Engineering d) Civil Engineering Answer: b 2. The term Artificial Intelligence was coined by: a) Alan Turing b) John McCarthy c) Marvin Minsky d) Herbert Simon Answer: b 3. According to John McCarthy, AI is: a) Study of computer hardware b) Science and engineering of making intelligent machines c) Study of human psychology d) Database management Answer: b 4. Machine learning allows systems to: a) Follow hard-coded rules b) Learn from data c) Avoid computation d) Replace databases Answer: b 13. text: Syllabus: Fundamentals of Artificial Intelligence (AI) 1. Introduction to Artificial Intelligence Definition, concept, scope, importance, and evolution of AI. 2. Definitions and Perspectives of AI John McCarthy’s definition, Russell and Norvig’s definition, AI as intelligent agents. 3. Goals and Objectives of AI Learning, reasoning, problem solving, knowledge representation, perception, decision-making, and NLP. 4. Types of Artificial Intelligence Narrow AI, General AI, and Super AI. 5. Core Components of AI Systems Data, algorithms, and models. 6. Fundamental Areas of Artificial Intelligence Machine Learning, Knowledge Representation, Reasoning and Inference, Search, NLP, Computer Vision, Robotics. 7. Machine Learning in AI Supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement learning. 8. Search and Problem Solving State space representation and search strategies. 9. Knowledge Representation and Reasoning Logical reasoning and inference mechanisms. 10. Artificial Intelligence Agents Concept of agents, agent–environment interaction, types of agents. 11. AI vs Machine Learning vs Deep Learning Relationship and differences. 12. Applications of Artificial Intelligence Healthcare, finance, education, transportation, manufacturing, customer support. 13. Advantages of Artificial Intelligence Automation, accuracy, efficiency, and availability. 14. Limitations of Artificial Intelligence Cost, data dependency, lack of creativity, ethical concerns. 15. Ethical and Responsible AI Bias, fairness, transparency, privacy, and accountability. 16. Future Scope of Artificial Intelligence Explainable AI, Edge AI, human–AI collaboration, responsible AI. 17. Summary Role, potential, and challenges of AI.

text: OpenCV Introduction to OpenCV (Open Source Computer Vision Library) What is OpenCV? OpenCV (Open Source Computer Vision Library) is an open-source library designed for computer vision, image processing, and real-time video analysis. It provides a large collection of optimized algorithms that allow computers to understand and process visual data such as images and videos. OpenCV is widely used in academics, research, and industry because it is: • Free and open source • Fast and efficient • Cross-platform • Easy to integrate with machine learning and deep learning frameworks History and Development of OpenCV • Developed by Intel in 1999 • Initially aimed at real-time computer vision applications • Later supported by Willow Garage and Itseez • Currently maintained by OpenCV.org • Written mainly in C++, with interfaces for Python, Java, MATLAB, etc. Why OpenCV is Important Modern applications require machines to: • Detect faces and objects • Track motion • Recognize patterns • Process live video streams OpenCV provides ready-to-use tools to solve these problems efficiently without implementing algorithms from scratch. Key Features of OpenCV 1. Open Source and Free • Licensed under Apache 2.0 • Can be used in commercial and academic projects 2. Cross-Platform Support • Windows • Linux • macOS • Android • iOS 3. Multi-Language Support • C++ • Python (most popular) • Java • MATLAB bindings Applications of OpenCV • Face detection and recognition • Object detection and tracking • Gesture recognition • Optical Character Recognition (OCR) • Medical image analysis • Surveillance systems • Autonomous vehicles • Augmented Reality (AR) Advantages of OpenCV • Real-time performance • Extensive documentation and community support • Easy integration with AI/ML models • Hardware acceleration support (GPU, CUDA) Limitations of OpenCV • Steep learning curve for beginners • Limited deep learning training support • Performance depends on hardware • Manual tuning often required

text: Syllabus: OpenCV (Open Source Computer Vision Library) 1. Introduction to OpenCV • Definition of OpenCV (Open Source Computer Vision Library) • Purpose of OpenCV in computer vision and image processing • Role of OpenCV in real-time video analysis • Importance of OpenCV in modern computer vision applications 2. Characteristics of OpenCV • Open-source nature of OpenCV • Free availability for academic and commercial use • Fast and efficient performance • Cross-platform compatibility • Integration capability with machine learning and deep learning frameworks 3. History and Development of OpenCV • Development of OpenCV by Intel (1999) • Initial focus on real-time computer vision applications • Contributions from Willow Garage and Itseez • Current maintenance by OpenCV.org • Programming languages supported (C++, Python, Java, MATLAB) 4. Importance of OpenCV in Computer Vision • Need for automated visual understanding • Face and object detection • Motion tracking • Pattern recognition • Live video stream processing • Advantages of ready-to-use vision algorithms 5. Key Features of OpenCV 5.1 Open Source and Licensing • Apache 2.0 license • Usage in commercial and academic projects 5.2 Cross-Platform Support • Windows • Linux • macOS • Android • iOS 5.3 Multi-Language Support • C++ • Python • Java • MATLAB bindings 6. Applications of OpenCV • Face detection and recognition • Object detection and tracking • Gesture recognition • Optical Character Recognition (OCR) • Medical image analysis • Surveillance systems • Autonomous vehicles • Augmented Reality (AR) 7. Advantages of OpenCV • Real-time processing capability • Large community and documentation support • Easy integration with AI and ML models • Hardware acceleration using GPU and CUDA 8. Limitations of OpenCV • Steep learning curve for beginners • Limited support for deep learning model training • Dependency on hardware performance • Requirement of manual parameter tuning 9. Summary • OpenCV as a core library for computer vision • Importance in academic, research, and industrial applications • Role of OpenCV in bridging traditional computer vision and AI
subject: OpenCV

text: Introduction to Python What is Python? Python is a high-level, interpreted, general-purpose programming language known for its simplicity and readability. It is widely used in academics, research, and industry. History of Python Python was created by Guido van Rossum and released in 1991. It is maintained by the Python Software Foundation. Features of Python  Simple and easy to learn  Interpreted language  High-level language  Object-oriented  Portable  Free and open source Programming Paradigms  Procedural Programming  Object-Oriented Programming  Functional Programming Applications of Python  Web development  Data Science  Machine Learning & AI  Computer Vision  Automation and scripting  Scientific computing Python Interpreter Python code is executed line by line using the Python interpreter. Programs can be run in interactive or script mode. Variables and Data Types Python is dynamically typed. Common data types include int, float, string, list, tuple, set, and dictionary. Python Keywords Keywords are reserved words such as if, else, for, while, def, class, and import. Python Libraries Popular libraries include NumPy, Pandas, Matplotlib, OpenCV, TensorFlow, and PyTorch. Advantages of Python  Easy to learn  Large community support  Rapid development  Extensive libraries Limitations of Python  Slower execution speed  Not suitable for low-level programming  GIL limits multi-threading Summary Python is a versatile and beginner-friendly language used in modern technologies such as AI, ML, and Data Science.
subject: Python

Python was created by: a) Dennis Ritchie b) James Gosling c) Guido van Rossum d) Bjarne Stroustrup Answer: c 3. Python was first released in: a) 1985 b) 1991 c) 1995 d) 2000 Answer: b 4. Python follows which programming paradigm? a) Procedural only b) Object-Oriented only c) Functional only d) Multiple paradigms Answer: d 8. text: Syllabus: Introduction to Python 1. Introduction to Python Definition, characteristics, importance, and areas of use. 2. History and Evolution of Python Creator, year of development, naming, Python Software Foundation. 3. Features of Python Simple syntax, high-level, interpreted, object-oriented, portable, open source. 4. Programming Paradigms Procedural, Object-Oriented, and Functional programming. 5. Python Interpreter and Execution Role of interpreter, interactive mode, script mode. 6. Python Variables Concept of variables, dynamic typing, naming rules. 7. Python Data Types Numeric, Boolean, String, List, Tuple, Set, Dictionary. 8. Python Keywords Definition and commonly used keywords. 9. Python Libraries and Ecosystem NumPy, Pandas, Matplotlib, OpenCV, TensorFlow, PyTorch. 10. Applications of Python Web development, Data Science, AI/ML, Computer Vision, Automation. 11. Advantages of Python Ease of learning, large community, rapid development. 12. Limitations of Python Slower execution, GIL, not suitable for low-level programming. 13. Summary and Future Scope Role of Python in modern technologies.
